observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the concerned employees submit within 30 days from receipt of the AOM, the liquidation reports and its supporting documents, otherwise, restitute/ return immediately the amount of their unliquidated cash advances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
require the concerned employees to submit within 30 days from receipt of this report, the liquidation report and its supporting documents, otherwise, restitute/return immediately the amount of the unliquidated cash advance; 

stop the grant of cash advances to officials and employees with outstanding cash advances;

issue a directive to the Municipal Treasurer to withhold the salaries of officials and employees who failed to liquidate their cash advances, based on the recommendations of the Municipal Accountant, and;

file the request for authority to write off the dormant unliquidated cash advances to the COA Audit Team Leader (ATL) and/or Supervising Auditor (SA) after exerting efforts to demand settlement of the accounts when the circumstances would warrant.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
demand from the accountable officers with unliquidated cash advances, the immediate settlement, refund or submission of liquidation reports on cash advances in which purpose have been served;

recommend to the Municipal Mayor the withholding of salaries of the accountable officers who continue to fail to submit their Liquidation Reports within the period prescribed by regulations;

prepare the schedule of dormant unliquidated cash advances by accountable officer/debtor/government entity and by account, to support the request for write-off, after exerting effort to demand settlement of the accounts, and;

discontinue processing DVs for grants of additional cash advance to officials and employees with unliquidated previous cash advances to avoid accumulation thereof.

We also recommended that the Municipal Treasurer withhold the salaries of officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances, as directed by the Municipal Mayor.

We recommended that the Municipal Engineer and the General Services Officer accomplish the following: 

complete the conduct of inventory of the LGU’s local roads; and prepare an accurate Inventory of Local Roads and reconcile with accounting records, and;  

submit the Inventory of Local Roads to DILG immediately and every three years thereafter, without need for demand from the said Office.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer to:
Diligently account/reconcile the year-end balances of the Due to GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and Philhealth accounts, ensuring that any necessary adjustments or corrections are properly recorded;
Ensure the proper and timely remittances of the Contributions and other payable to GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and Philhealth, to avoid any impositions of penalties and interest thereof.  Also, coordinate regularly to said Offices in case of deficiencies committed relative thereto and the same for settlement thereof;
Expedite the transmittal of payroll from the Treasurer’s Office to Accounting Office for an accurate and timely recording on the withholding and remittances of Contributions and other payable to GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and Philhealth Offices; and
Henceforth, adhere with the applicable laws, rules and regulations on the withholding and remittances of Contributions and/or payables to GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and Philhealth.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to review first the completeness of the required supporting documents and ensure the same that it is in the required forms, prior to the grant of cash advance for confidential expenses to the designated Special Disbursing Officer;

 We also recommended to direct the concerned local official/s to facilitate the submission of the liquidation report of cash advances for confidential expenses to the Office of the COA Chairperson through ICFAU; and

 We recommended further to direct the Municipal Accountant to record the liquidation only upon receipt of the liquidation report with the transmittal letter duly stamped received by the ICFAU and a copy of such transmittal letter be forwarded to the COA Audit Team Leader.

We reiterated the recommendation, with modification, that the Municipal Accountant should: 

require all End-User Units to submit all documents for the procurement of goods and services charged from the current year appropriation, the obligations of the suppliers having been duly fulfilled, based on the contract, during the current year, to facilitate the recording of the expenses in the books of accounts of the municipality; 

prepare adjusting entry to drop from Accounts Payable account the unsubstantiated claims as well as to effect corrections on the erroneously recorded transactions;

record only the accounts payable which were obligated and have complete supporting documents.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of PPE in accordance with COA Circular 2020-006 and instruct the Chairperson of the Inventory Committee to:

prepare and submit to the Municipal Mayor for his approval, a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) indicating therein the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, cut-off date and schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory;

conduct the physical inventory within the period identified in the PIP and tag all counted properties of the municipality;

categorize the accounted PPE using the PPSAS account classification in the RPCPPE and prepare the report within 60 days from the completion of the physical inventory and furnish a copy of the report to the COA Team Leader, Municipal Accountant and Head of the Property Unit of the Municipality.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

effect the necessary adjusting journal entries on the Depreciation of the road component accounts to establish the correct balances of the road network components in the financial statements;

earnestly comply with the required maintenance of subsidiary records for the roads network components to ascertain the reliability of the PPE account as presented in the financial statements; and

in coordination with the General Services Officer conduct a reconciliation of the PPEs included in the RPCPPE with the recorded properties in the books of accounts of the Municipality and prepare the necessary report on the results of the reconciliation and submit to the Municipal Mayor for his appropriate action, in cases of non-existing/ missing properties, if any.

Finally, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor, together with the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer, perform the procedures to account for non-existing/missing properties as a result of the reconciliation conducted to facilitate the disposition of these items in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 to reflect a reliable balance of the PPE account in the Financial Statement.

